# Design quality bar

## When this applies

Design, redesign, restyle, "match screenshot", "make it look better", "fix UI", layout/nav redesigns, or any visual polish request.

## The bar

Output must feel like a **deliberate redesign**: clearer hierarchy, better spacing rhythm, consistent chrome, improved scanability. If the result still looks like the old UI with new colors/borders, you failed.

## Do

- Study reference screenshots carefully (`Read` the image files — don't guess from filenames)
- Prefer **structural** layout changes when flow/density/grouping is broken — not only `className` tweaks
- Use ShopRally brand (navy / light-blue / red-orange); do **not** copy AutoLeap teal or Tekmetric colored rail headers
- Read and follow `.claude/skills/frontend-design/SKILL.md` and the user's frontend design rules
- Keep all existing functionality and click handlers unless asked to change behavior

## Don't

- Ship "same layout, slightly different border/padding"
- Narrow/widen panels randomly without matching spacing intent from the reference
- Leave inconsistent patterns across sibling screens (settings tabs, drawers, dialogs, etc.)

## Model choice

For design-heavy tasks, prefer a high-capability model for the implementing subagent when the parent can choose (e.g. `claude-4.6-sonnet`, `claude-opus`, or `gpt-5.x` high tiers from the available list). Do **not** default to the weakest/fastest model for redesigns.

## Verify

After redesign, compare against the reference. Call out remaining gaps honestly — do not claim parity you didn't achieve.
